sections.paragraphs:
{{Manner of articulation}}
<div style="float: right;">{{IPA notice}}</div>

'''Approximants''' are [[phone (phonetics)|speech sounds]] that involve the [[Speech organ|articulators]] approaching each other but not narrowly enough<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Ladefoged|1975|p=277}}</ref> nor with enough articulatory precision<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Martínez-Celdrán|2004|p=201}}, citing {{Harvcoltxt|Ladefoged|Maddieson|1996}}</ref> to create [[manner of articulation|turbulent airflow]]. Therefore, approximants fall between [[fricative consonant|fricatives]], which do produce a turbulent airstream, and [[vowel]]s, which produce no turbulence.{{sfnp|Martínez-Celdrán|2004|p=201}} This class is composed of sounds like {{IPA|[ɹ]}} (as in ''rest'') and [[semivowels]] like {{IPA|[j]}} and {{IPA|[w]}} (as in ''yes'' and ''west'', respectively), as well as [[Lateral consonant|lateral]] approximants like {{IPA|[l]}} (as in ''less'').{{sfnp|Martínez-Celdrán|2004|p=201}}

*[[bilabial approximant]] {{IPA|[β̞]}} (usually transcribed {{angbr IPA|β}})
*[[labiodental approximant]] {{IPA|[ʋ]}}
*[[dental approximant]] {{IPA|[ð̞]}} (usually transcribed {{angbr IPA|ð}})
*[[alveolar approximant]] {{IPA|[ɹ]}}
*[[retroflex approximant]] {{IPA|[ɻ&thinsp;]}} (a vocalic {{IPA|[ɚ]}})
*[[palatal approximant]] {{IPA|[j]}} (a vocalic {{IPA|[i]}})
*[[velar approximant]] {{IPA|[ɰ]}} (a vocalic {{IPA|[ɯ]}})
*[[uvular approximant]] {{IPA|[ʁ̞]}} (usually transcribed {{angbr IPA|ʁ}})
*[[pharyngeal approximant]] {{IPA|[ʕ̞]}} (a vocalic {{IPA|[ɑ]}}; usually transcribed {{angbr IPA|ʕ}})
*[[breathy-voiced glottal approximant]] {{IPA|[ɦ]}}
*[[creaky-voiced glottal approximant]] {{IPA|[ʔ̞]}}

In lateral approximants, the center of tongue makes solid contact with the roof of the mouth. However, the defining location is the side of the tongue, which only approaches the teeth.

* [[voiceless alveolar lateral approximant]] {{IPA|[l̥]}}
* [[Alveolar lateral approximant|voiced alveolar lateral approximant]] {{IPA|[l]}}
* [[retroflex lateral approximant]] {{IPA|[ɭ]}}
* [[voiceless palatal lateral approximant]] {{IPA|[ʎ̥]}}
* [[Palatal lateral approximant|voiced palatal lateral approximant]] {{IPA|[ʎ]}}
* [[velar lateral approximant]] {{IPA|[ʟ]}}
* [[uvular lateral approximant]] {{IPA|[ʟ̠]}}

Voiceless approximants are rarely distinguished from voiceless fricatives. [[Iaai language|Iaai]] has an unusually large number of them, with {{IPA|/l̥ ɥ̊ w̥/}} contrasting with {{IPA|/l ɥ w/}} (as well as a large number of [[voiceless nasal]]s). Attested voiceless approximants are:<ref>Bickford & Floyd (2006), augmented by sources at individual articles for the glottal approximants</ref>

*[[voiceless alveolar lateral approximant]] {{IPA|[l̥]}}
*[[voiceless velar lateral approximant]] {{IPA|[ʟ̥]}}
*[[voiceless labiodental approximant]] {{IPA|[ʋ̥]}}
*[[voiceless alveolar approximant]] {{IPA|[ɹ̥]}}
*[[voiceless palatal approximant]] {{IPA|[j̊]}}
*[[voiceless labialized palatal approximant]] {{IPA|[ɥ̊]}} or {{IPA|[j̊ʷ]}}
*[[voiceless velar approximant]] {{IPA|[ɰ̊]}}
*[[voiceless labio-velar approximant|voiceless labialized velar approximant]] {{IPA|[ʍ]}} or {{IPA|[w̥]}}
*[[voiceless glottal approximant]] {{IPA|[h]}}
*[[voiceless nasal glottal approximant]] {{IPA|[h̃]}}

(Not to be confused with 'nasal continuant', which is a synonym for [[nasal consonant]])

Examples are:
*[[nasal palatal approximant]] {{IPA|[j̃]}}
*[[nasal labialized velar approximant]] {{IPA|[w̃]}}
*[[voiceless nasal glottal approximant]] {{IPA|[h̃]}}

In [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], the '''nasal glides''' {{IPA|[j̃]}} and {{IPA|[w̃]}} historically became {{IPA|/ɲ/}} and {{IPA|/m/}} in some words.  In [[Edo language|Edo]], the nasalized allophones of the approximants {{IPA|/j/}} and {{IPA|/w/}} are nasal occlusives, {{IPA|[ɲ]}} and {{IPA|[ŋʷ]}}.

What are transcribed as nasal approximants may include non-syllabic elements of [[nasal vowel]]s or diphthongs.
